    <h2>Understanding Vehicle Recalls</h2>
    <p>A vehicle recall occurs when a manufacturer or NHTSA determines that a vehicle, equipment, car seat, or tire creates an unreasonable safety risk or fails to meet minimum safety standards. When a recall is issued, the manufacturer must fix the problem at no cost to the vehicle owner.</p>

    <h2>Recall Statistics</h2>
    <p>According to NHTSA, there are approximately 30,000 to 40,000 recalls issued each year across all vehicle types in the United States, affecting tens of millions of vehicles. In 2024 alone, major recalls included issues with airbag systems, brake components, fuel system leaks, and software glitches in advanced driver assistance systems.</p>

